  "prompt": "What are some good auto biographies?",
  "response": "There are many powerful and inspiring autobiographies that offer insight into the lives and minds of influential individuals. Here are some noteworthy ones that you might find compelling:\n\n1. **\"The Diary of a Young Girl\" by Anne Frank** - An intimate look into the life of a young Jewish girl hiding from the Nazis during World War II.\n\n2. **\"Long Walk to Freedom\" by Nelson Mandela** - The life story of the South African leader's fight against apartheid.\n\n3. **\"The Story of My Experiments with Truth\" by Mahatma Gandhi** - Gandhi's account of his early life, development of his political views, and his philosophy of nonviolent resistance.\n\n4. **\"I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings\" by Maya Angelou** - A poignant coming-of-age story addressing issues of identity, racism, and literacy.\n\n5. **\"Bossypants\" by Tina Fey** - A comedic autobiography by the well-known comedian and actress.\n\n6. **\"Becoming\" by Michelle Obama** - The memoir of the former First Lady of the United States, exploring her roots and her role in the White House.\n\n7. **\"The Autobiography of Malcolm X\" by Malcolm X and Alex Haley** - A powerful narrative of the life of the influential African American leader and his transformation.\n\n8. **\"Educated\" by Tara Westover** - A memoir about a woman's quest for knowledge that takes her from a survivalist family in Idaho to earning a PhD from Cambridge University.\n\n9. **\"Just Kids\" by Patti Smith** - A touching memoir of the artist's relationship with the photographer Robert Mapplethorpe.\n\n10. **\"Born a Crime: Stories from a South African Childhood\" by Trevor Noah** - A comic yet insightful account of Noah\u2019s life growing up as the son of a white Swiss father and a black Xhosa mother in apartheid South Africa.\n\nThese autobiographies span diverse backgrounds and experiences, offering a range of perspectives and insights into different lives and cultures.",
